[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:KJ965.AK843.75.4 A83.J965.93.KQ52 Q4.QT7.AJ6.AT986 T72.2.KQT842.J73"]
[VersionToken "f1db28dfcc1a39cc12518e0ee948922fa81d516a27e84243279eea90ab89e4c7"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
1S Pass 2C Pass 2H Pass 2NT Pass 3H Pass 4H Pass Pass Pass
{North opens 1\S.  So far you know you belong in game, but you don't know which game.  What do you bid first?
You respond 2\C, natural and forcing the partnership to game.
North now bids his \H suit.
At this point you figurer North for 5 \Ss and 4 \Hs. What should you rebid?
You cannot support either of North's Majors, but with a good stopper in the fourth suit you bid 2NT. The game force is still on and North may not pass this bid.
North bids 3\H, indicating that this is also a 5-card suit. What do you rebid now? 

Now you can bid the \H game, knowing there is an 8-card fit.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "2"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "S:983.82.T82.AKJT8 AJT74.KT7.A95.72 KQ2.J64.J74.6543 65.AQ953.KQ63.Q9"]
[VersionToken "0833454e58ff7910a6a8fccd4724605aa9786d75a91016f42c61ec870410b72b"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "S"]
Pass 1S Pass 2H Pass 3H Pass 4H Pass Pass Pass
{What do you open with this hand?
You opens 1\S and East, responds 2\H. Note that this promises a 5-card or longer \H suit.  (2 of a minor only promises 4+).
What do you rebid?
Knowing that East has 5, you bid 3\H to confirm the trump suit.
East bids 4\h.  

East went straight to game, showing a minimum opener and no slam interest.
You are also satisfied to just play at game.
2/1 is a good bidding method, and here, 4\H is a good contract. But you can see that it is not a laydown - there is no bidding system that will always reach 100% contracts. In this hand a 3-3 \D split will provide the 10th trick, or if that fails, taking 2 \S finesses provides a 75% chance of success.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "S:AK9652.T983.4.A8 JT8.J4.AT9853.74 7.AK75.K762.KQT6 Q43.Q62.QJ.J9532"]
[VersionToken "2ce9f2089ccaf4a73f9044dac5cedc65d2c2321d8d4e040affd4e9034c48af16"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "S"]
1S Pass 2C Pass 2H Pass 3H Pass 4H Pass Pass Pass
{South opens 1\S.  
You have 15 HCP, but you only have 4\hs, so you can't bid 2\H (this would promise a 5-card suit).  So instead you bid clubs.  This is natural and game-forcing, but only promises 4+ clubs.
Note that holding two 4-card minors you bid them up-the-line, just as in standard bidding.
South rebids 2\h.  This shows at least 4 hearts.  What do you rebid now?
Your 3\h bid confirms hearts as trump.  There's no worry partner might pass - we are in a game forcing auction.
South raises to 4\h, showing no slam interest.  

We don't have enough for slam opposite a minimum opener, so we just pass.
Note South's decision to show the poor 4-card heart suit for their second bid, instead of showing the 6th spade.  In a GF sequence, it's more important to tell about 4 more cards then 1 more card.  South will always have the chance to rebid spades later if there is no heart fit.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "W:AK92.AQ983.85.86 J64.75.63.AQT432 875.K4.AQJT7.K97 QT3.JT62.K942.J5"]
[VersionToken "3bb7dcf0323aa6fa6885ebb26c6fd341b4ac97707eed014d09094a60724d9b58"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "W"]
1H Pass 2D Pass 2S Pass 2NT Pass 3NT Pass Pass Pass
{West opens 1\H - how do you respond?
West next bids 2\S, showing the other Major suit.  In standard bidding this is a Reverse, showing a strong hand with 5\hs and 4\ss.  But after a 2/1 GF response, West doesn't need extra values to show their 4-card spade suit.  What should you rebid?
You assume West to be 4-5 in the Majors, and since you can't support either one, you bid 2NT.
If West actually has 6 \Hs (or 5 \Ss) he would rebid the suit. Your 2NT bid guarantees a stopper in the fourth suit.

West does not have either 6 \Hs or 5 \Ss so he just bids 3NT.  Notice that West never once considered the possibility of passing what might be a misfit - the initial 2/1 response unconditionally forced the partnership to reach a game somewhere.}

